---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

export const prerender = true;

// Using plain JS objects (no complex TS types) to avoid build errors
const stories: any = {

  meera: {
    name: 'Meera', age: 39, city: 'Pune', occupation: 'Software Team Lead',
    color: '#2D5F7A',
    title: 'The Doctor Said It Was Stress',
    sections: [
      { text: 'Three doctors in fourteen months. That is my number.' },
      { text: 'The first one said it was work stress. He asked me how many hours I was putting in, I said sixty sometimes more, and he nodded like he had solved it. Take a break. Reduce screen time. Try yoga. He wrote it on a prescription pad. Yoga. For what I now know were hot flashes, heart palpitations, and a memory so shot I had started writing my own name on sticky notes in case I forgot it mid-thought.' },
      { ig: { head: "What Was Happening in Meera's Body", rows: [
        { label: 'Oestrogen spikes and crashes', color: 'peach', text: 'Levels became unpredictable instead of following a steady monthly pattern' },
        { label: 'Hypothalamus confused', color: 'peach', text: "The brain's thermostat misreads signals and triggers sudden heat and sweating" },
        { label: 'Nervous system activated', color: 'muted', text: 'Heart rate increases during a flash. This is what feels like palpitations' },
        { label: 'Brain chemistry disrupted', color: 'muted', text: 'Oestrogen supports memory and word retrieval. When it fluctuates, both slow down' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'The second doctor ran a thyroid test, found nothing, and told me I was probably anxious. She was not unkind about it. She prescribed something for anxiety and sent me home. I took the tablets for three weeks. Nothing changed except I felt slightly numb and slightly embarrassed, as if I had been manufacturing symptoms for attention.' },
      { text: 'The third doctor was a gynaecologist. My cousin had seen her and mentioned perimenopause almost as an aside, the way you mention something you are not sure is relevant. I almost did not make the appointment. I was 39. Perimenopause was something that happened to your mother. Your mother\'s mother.' },
      { text: 'She asked me to describe my periods. I told her: irregular for the past eight months, sometimes 21 days apart, sometimes 45, once so heavy I soaked through my clothes at a client meeting and had to walk out pretending to take a call. She listened without interrupting. Then she ordered a hormone panel, FSH, LH, AMH, oestradiol, things the previous two doctors had never mentioned.' },
      { text: 'The results came back within a week. She called me herself. Meera, your hormones are consistent with early perimenopause.' },
      { text: 'I sat in my car in the parking lot of my office and cried. Not because it was devastating. Because someone had finally said a real thing. After fourteen months of being handed explanations that did not fit, someone had given me the right one.' },
      { text: 'I am not fixed. There is no fixing. But I am managing it now. I know what is happening in my body and why, and that is more than I had before. If I could say anything to the version of myself sitting across from Doctor Number One being told to try yoga: push harder. Ask for the blood tests. You are not imagining it.' },
    ]
  },

  divya: {
    name: 'Divya', age: 38, city: 'Hyderabad', occupation: 'Works from home, two children',
    color: '#3D7A5F',
    title: 'Nobody Told Me It Could Happen at 38',
    sections: [
      { text: 'I found out I was in perimenopause the same week my daughter turned seven. She was blowing out her candles and I was standing behind her thinking: something is very wrong with me and I do not know what.' },
      { text: 'It had been building for almost a year. The sleep, or the complete absence of it. Waking at 3am completely alert, heart going faster than it should, mind already running through everything I had not done, every bill, every school form, every unanswered message. Lying there for two hours before giving up. Getting through the day on three hours of sleep and two cups of coffee and a kind of desperation I had no name for.' },
      { text: 'The rage was the thing I am least proud of. Not anger. Rage. Sudden, disproportionate, frightening to me as much as to anyone else. My husband would leave a cup on the wrong shelf and something would rise in me that felt completely out of scale. I would see it happening and not be able to stop it. Afterwards I would feel so ashamed. So unlike myself.' },
      { ig: { head: "What Was Happening in Divya's Body", rows: [
        { label: 'Oestrogen falling', color: 'peach', text: 'Triggers a drop in serotonin, the brain chemical responsible for mood stability' },
        { label: 'Progesterone falling first', color: 'peach', text: 'Reduces GABA, the calming neurotransmitter. The emotional buffer thins' },
        { label: 'Small triggers, big reactions', color: 'muted', text: 'The nervous system cannot absorb frustration the way it used to. This is chemistry, not character' },
        { label: '3am waking', color: 'muted', text: 'Cortisol patterns shift in perimenopause, producing early waking with a racing mind' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'I thought it was depression. My mother had it, I had watched it from close enough to be afraid of it my whole adult life. I went to see a psychiatrist. She was thorough and careful and after two sessions she said: before we go further, I want to rule out a hormonal cause. Have you seen a gynaecologist recently?' },
      { text: 'I had not. Why would I? I was 38.' },
      { text: 'The gynaecologist explained perimenopause to me the way you explain something to someone who has never heard of it, which I essentially had not, not as something that could happen to me. I had always thought of it as a distant event. Post-50. After your children left home. Not now, in the middle of everything.' },
      { text: 'What nobody tells you is that it can start in your late 30s. That early perimenopause is not rare. That the symptoms, the sleep, the mood, the brain that stops cooperating, can arrive years before your periods change significantly. I wish I had known that earlier. I wish someone had said it out loud so that when it arrived, I would have recognised it instead of spending a year being frightened of myself.' },
      { text: 'I am in a better place now. Not a perfect place. I am not sure perfect exists anymore. But I know what is happening. And knowing, it turns out, is most of the battle.' },
    ]
  },

  ananya: {
    name: 'Ananya', age: 41, city: 'Mumbai', occupation: 'Senior Manager',
    color: '#8A5230',
    title: 'My Husband Thought I Was Becoming Someone Else',
    sections: [
      { text: 'We had been married for twelve years. Twelve years is long enough that you think you know each other completely. Long enough that when something changes, the other person notices before you do.' },
      { text: 'He said it on a Sunday morning, quietly, while I was making chai. You have not been yourself lately. I asked him what that meant. He said: shorter. More angry. Like you are always on the edge of something.' },
      { text: 'He was not wrong. I had been snapping at him, at our son, at colleagues who did not deserve it. I would say something in a meeting that I would immediately regret. I would lie awake composing apologies for things I had said and things I had only thought. The gap between who I was and who I was behaving like had never felt this wide.' },
      { ig: { head: "What Was Happening in Ananya's Body", rows: [
        { label: 'Oestrogen spiking and crashing', color: 'peach', text: 'Not steadily declining but swinging wildly, which disrupts mood more than a slow decline would' },
        { label: 'Progesterone declining', color: 'peach', text: 'The calming, stabilising hormone falls first. The emotional brake weakens' },
        { label: 'Serotonin destabilised', color: 'muted', text: 'Oestrogen supports serotonin. When it fluctuates, the threshold for frustration lowers' },
        { label: 'Not character change', color: 'green', text: 'The nervous system is running without its usual hormonal buffer. This is recognisable and treatable' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'What he did not know, what I did not know, was that I was not becoming someone else. My oestrogen was crashing and spiking and crashing again on a schedule that had nothing to do with my intentions or my character or how much I loved my family.' },
      { text: 'I told him about perimenopause six weeks after my gynaecologist explained it to me. I had spent those six weeks feeling like I needed to understand it fully before I could explain it to him. Sitting at the kitchen table, I showed him what I had been reading. He listened. He asked a few questions. Then he said: so this is what has been happening. Not a question. An understanding.' },
      { text: 'Things did not change overnight. But he stopped interpreting my reactions as personal, and I stopped being ashamed of having them. That shift, that small factual shift, changed what was happening between us more than anything else could have.' },
      { text: 'He did not need me to be fixed. He needed to understand what was happening. They both do, our husbands. We just have to tell them.' },
    ]
  },

  kavitha: {
    name: 'Kavitha', age: 43, city: 'Bangalore', occupation: 'Product Manager, 15 years',
    color: '#1A2D4A',
    title: 'I Thought I Was Losing My Mind at Work',
    sections: [
      { text: 'I have been in product management for fifteen years. I am the person teams come to when they need clarity. I am the one who remembers the meeting from three months ago and what was decided and who said what. That memory, that particular sharpness, was not something I thought about. It was just who I was.' },
      { text: 'And then, at 42, it started leaving.' },
      { text: 'Not all at once. Slowly. I would be mid-sentence in a presentation and the word I needed, a completely normal professional word I had used a hundred times, would simply not be there. I would pause. Look at the screen. Keep talking around it. Nobody noticed, or if they did, they were polite enough not to say anything.' },
      { ig: { head: "What Was Happening in Kavitha's Brain", rows: [
        { label: 'Oestrogen supports acetylcholine', color: 'green', text: 'Acetylcholine is the neurotransmitter for memory, attention, and word retrieval' },
        { label: 'Oestrogen fluctuating', color: 'peach', text: 'Acetylcholine signalling becomes inconsistent. Words take longer to arrive' },
        { label: 'Blood flow reduced', color: 'muted', text: 'Oestrogen increases blood flow to verbal memory areas. When it drops, processing slows' },
        { label: 'Not progressive', color: 'green', text: 'Unlike dementia, perimenopause brain fog fluctuates. Worse some weeks, better others' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'But I noticed. Every single time.' },
      { text: 'I started over-preparing. I wrote detailed notes for every meeting. I sent myself voice memos with things I needed to remember. I arrived fifteen minutes early to every call to review what had been discussed. I was doing the work of two brains just to perform at the level one brain used to manage automatically.' },
      { text: 'The worst part was not the forgetting itself. It was the fear underneath the forgetting. My father had Alzheimer\'s. I watched what that took from him, and from us. When my memory started slipping, that fear sat behind every blank moment like a shadow.' },
      { text: 'When I finally brought it up with a doctor, a psychiatrist I had been seeing for what I thought was burnout, she said something I will not forget: this is not progressive. It does not get worse over time the way Alzheimer\'s does. It fluctuates. Worse some weeks, better others. That alone tells you it is not what you are afraid of.' },
      { text: 'Perimenopause brain fog fluctuates. Dementia does not. That distinction saved me months of quiet, private terror.' },
      { text: 'I am still in product management. Still the person teams come to. I still write more notes than I used to, and I have made peace with that. The sharpness has come back, not completely, not always, but enough to know I did not lose myself. I just went through something that nobody told me was coming.' },
    ]
  },

  sunita: {
    name: 'Sunita', age: 37, city: 'Jaipur', occupation: 'Working mother, toddler at home',
    color: '#5A6B4E',
    title: 'Everyone Said I Was Too Young. I Believed Them.',
    sections: [
      { text: 'Thirty-seven. That is how old I was when it started. That is the number that made every doctor do a small double-take when I sat across from them.' },
      { text: 'Too young, my mother said. She was not unkind. She just could not fit it into what she knew. Menopause in her world happened to women in their fifties. Not her daughter, with a toddler still at home and a job she had fought to keep.' },
      { text: 'Too young, my first doctor said. He ran no tests. He told me my periods were probably irregular because of the stress of having a young child and going back to work. He told me the night sweats were anxiety. He told me to rest more.' },
      { ig: { head: "What Was Happening in Sunita's Body", rows: [
        { label: 'Anovulatory cycles', color: 'peach', text: 'The follicle develops but ovulation does not always happen. No ovulation means no progesterone' },
        { label: 'Cycle becomes unpredictable', color: 'peach', text: '21 days one month, 45 the next. This is a hormonal signal, not stress' },
        { label: 'Night sweats', color: 'muted', text: 'Oestrogen fluctuation disrupts the hypothalamus thermostat. The body tries to cool itself at night' },
        { label: 'Early perimenopause is real', color: 'green', text: 'It can begin in the mid to late 30s. Not rare. Just rarely discussed' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'I believed him. Why would I not? He was the doctor. I was the person who had never heard of early perimenopause. I went home and tried to rest more.' },
      { text: 'For almost a year, I tried to rest more.' },
      { text: 'What changed was a conversation at a family wedding, the kind you have standing near the food while children run past you. My cousin\'s wife, ten years older than me, mentioned offhand that she had been on HRT for three years. I asked her what it was like. She asked me why I was asking. I told her what had been happening to me. She looked at me with a particular kind of recognition and said: Sunita, you need to see a gynaecologist. Not a GP. A gynaecologist who deals with perimenopause specifically.' },
      { text: 'The tests took two weeks. The diagnosis took one appointment. Early perimenopause, confirmed, documented, real.' },
      { text: 'I have thought a lot about that year of being told I was too young. About how much I accommodated that explanation because it came from authority. About how different things might have been if someone had mentioned that this can happen in your 30s.' },
      { text: 'I am mentioning it now. It can happen in your 30s. If your body is telling you something, find someone who will listen.' },
    ]
  },

  priya: {
    name: 'Priya', age: 40, city: 'Chennai', occupation: 'Teacher',
    color: '#B84A2E',
    title: 'I Was Ashamed of the Word Menopause',
    sections: [
      { text: 'In my family, menopause was not a word we said. It moved through conversations sideways, never directly. My mother referred to it as that time when she spoke of it at all. My aunts would lower their voices. It sat in the same category as things that were too intimate, too bodily, too much.' },
      { text: 'So when the symptoms started at 40 and I eventually, finally, found out what they were, I did not tell anyone for four months.' },
      { text: 'Not my husband. Not my mother, who would have, in her way, understood. Not my closest friend, who had told me things I know she has told no one else. Nobody.' },
      { text: 'I carried it alone. And carrying it alone made everything worse. The anxiety sharper, the sleeplessness more frightening, the rage more shameful. There was no one to say this makes sense, or I have been through this, or simply I am here.' },
      { ig: { head: "What Silence Does to Perimenopause Symptoms", rows: [
        { label: 'Cortisol rises', color: 'peach', text: 'Sustained stress and social isolation raise cortisol, which amplifies every symptom' },
        { label: 'Sleep worsens', color: 'peach', text: 'High cortisol disrupts the sleep cycle further, creating a worsening loop' },
        { label: 'Anxiety intensifies', color: 'muted', text: "Without language for what is happening, the body's signals become frightening" },
        { label: 'Naming it helps', color: 'green', text: 'When the brain understands what is happening, the nervous system threat response reduces' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'The silence around menopause in Indian families is not malicious. It comes from a generation of women who were themselves not told anything, who were handed the experience with no language for it and made something out of it anyway. Our mothers were not trying to leave us unprepared. They were working with what they had.' },
      { text: 'But the silence has a cost. I felt, for those four months, like I was ageing badly and privately and wrong, like something was ending that was not supposed to end yet, and I had to carry the embarrassment of that alone.' },
      { text: 'I told my husband on a Tuesday evening. He listened for a long time. Then he said: why did you not tell me earlier? I did not have a good answer. I said: I think I was ashamed of the word.' },
      { text: 'He said: it is just a word.' },
      { text: 'I know it is not just a word. Words carry everything that has ever been said and not said around them. But he was trying, and the trying mattered.' },
      { text: 'I am saying the word now. Perimenopause. Menopause. Out loud, with my name attached to it. Because the silence cost me four months of unnecessary suffering, and I would rather someone else not pay the same.' },
    ]
  },

  lakshmi: {
    name: 'Lakshmi', age: 44, city: 'Kochi', occupation: 'School Administrator',
    color: '#7A4A8A',
    title: 'Two of Us Were Going Through It at Once',
    sections: [
      { text: 'My daughter turned fifteen the year my body stopped making sense. For a while I did not connect the two things. I only knew that our house had become a place of slammed doors and sudden tears, and that half of them were hers and half of them were mine.' },
      { text: 'She was in the thick of her own hormones. Moody, tender, furious, then laughing, then crying again. I had braced for that. Every mother is warned about the teenage years. What nobody warned me about was that I would be having my own version of it at exactly the same time, in the same kitchen, over the same small things.' },
      { text: 'We would collide. She would snap at me and something in me, something I could not hold back, would snap right back, far harder than the moment deserved. Then we would both retreat to our rooms, on opposite sides of the same storm, and I would sit on my bed wondering what had happened to the patient mother I used to be.' },
      { ig: { head: "Why Two Generations Can Peak Together", rows: [
        { label: 'Her rising hormones', color: 'peach', text: 'Adolescence brings surging, unstable hormones that heighten emotion and reactivity' },
        { label: 'Your falling hormones', color: 'peach', text: 'Perimenopause brings dropping progesterone and swinging oestrogen, thinning the emotional buffer' },
        { label: 'Same triggers, both raw', color: 'muted', text: 'Two nervous systems running without their usual steadiness, reacting to each other' },
        { label: 'Not a broken bond', color: 'green', text: 'Understanding the biology lets both people stop taking the reactions personally' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'The thing that changed it was not a solution. It was a piece of information. My gynaecologist explained perimenopause to me, and as she described the mood swings and the short fuse and the way small things now felt enormous, I sat there thinking: this is exactly what my daughter is going through, from the other end.' },
      { text: 'She was rising into her hormones. I was coming down out of mine. And we had met, by accident of timing, in the middle.' },
      { text: 'I told her about it, carefully, one evening. Not as an excuse, but as an explanation. I said, you and I are both having a hard time with our bodies right now, and some of the shouting is not really you and it is not really me. She looked at me for a long moment. Then she said, so we are basically the same. And we both laughed, which we had not done together in weeks.' },
      { text: 'It did not fix everything. But it gave us a shared language. Now, sometimes, in the middle of a rising argument, one of us will say hormones, and it lets a little air into the room.' },
      { text: 'I used to think I had to be the steady one while she went through her storm. It turned out we were in the same weather. Naming that, out loud, together, is the closest thing to shelter we have found.' },
    ]
  },

  rehana: {
    name: 'Rehana', age: 46, city: 'Lucknow', occupation: 'Runs the household of a joint family',
    color: '#A23E5C',
    title: 'There Was Nowhere in the House to Fall Apart',
    sections: [
      { text: 'In our house there are eleven people and no doors that truly close. I am the one who holds it together. The meals, the medicines for my husband\'s parents, the school runs, the endless small needs of a joint family. For twenty years I have been the still centre that everyone else turns around.' },
      { text: 'So when the flashes started, and the nights when I could not sleep, and the days when I felt I might weep into the daal for no reason, there was nowhere to put any of it. There was no room that was mine. There was no hour that was mine. There was always someone in the kitchen, someone calling my name, someone needing.' },
      { text: 'A hot flash would rise in me in the middle of cooking for everyone, and I would stand at the stove with sweat running down my back and my heart pounding, and I would simply keep stirring, because eleven people were waiting to eat.' },
      { ig: { head: "What Carrying Everyone Costs the Body", rows: [
        { label: 'No recovery time', color: 'peach', text: 'Constant caregiving keeps stress hormones high, which intensifies every perimenopause symptom' },
        { label: 'Sleep already broken', color: 'peach', text: 'Night sweats on top of early rising and late nights leave no room to restore' },
        { label: 'Needs go unspoken', color: 'muted', text: 'When a woman is the family\'s support, her own symptoms become invisible, even to her' },
        { label: 'Rest is medicine', color: 'green', text: 'Even small, protected pockets of rest lower the load and ease symptoms' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'In our family, a woman does not sit down in the afternoon. It is not done. My mother-in-law never did, and her mother never did. To rest is to be seen as lacking. So I did not rest, and I did not speak, and I told myself that whatever this was, it would pass if I just kept going.' },
      { text: 'It did not pass. It got heavier. And the heaviness started to show as sharpness, in my voice, in my hands, in the way I began to resent the very people I loved.' },
      { text: 'The one who noticed was my younger sister-in-law. She found me sitting on the back step one evening, which I never do, and she sat down beside me without a word. After a while she said, you are not yourself. And for the first time in months, someone had left a small opening, and I told her.' },
      { text: 'She did a simple thing. She began taking the kitchen from me for one hour each afternoon so I could lie down in the one empty room, with the fan on, and simply be a body that needed rest and not a woman who was needed. One hour. It changed more than I can explain.' },
      { text: 'I am learning, slowly and against everything I was taught, that I am allowed to be a person who is going through something. That holding the family together does not mean I have to disappear inside it. There is still nowhere in the house that is fully mine. But there is one hour. And for now, that one hour is where I am putting myself back together.' },
    ]
  },

  deepa: {
    name: 'Deepa', age: 41, city: 'Coimbatore', occupation: 'Bank Manager',
    color: '#2A6B6B',
    title: 'I Went Through It With No One to Turn To',
    sections: [
      { text: 'I never married, and I made my peace with that a long time ago. I built a life I am proud of, a career, close friends, a flat that is entirely mine. What I did not plan for was going through perimenopause with no one on the other side of the bed to say, are you alright, you do not seem yourself.' },
      { text: 'It is a particular kind of alone. Not lonely, exactly. I have people. But when you wake at 3am soaked in sweat and shaking, there is no one to reach for. When your body starts doing frightening, unfamiliar things, there is no one who witnesses it day after day and reflects it back to you, so you can know you are not imagining it.' },
      { text: 'For months I doubted myself in a way I never had. Was I overreacting? Was this normal tiredness, normal stress, normal ageing? Without a witness, I had no way to measure. I began to think I was becoming difficult, unstable, less than the capable woman I had always been.' },
      { ig: { head: "Why a Witness Matters So Much", rows: [
        { label: 'Symptoms feel unreal', color: 'peach', text: 'Without someone to reflect them back, hormonal changes can feel like imagination or overreaction' },
        { label: 'Self-doubt grows', color: 'peach', text: 'The anxiety of perimenopause plus isolation makes women question their own perception' },
        { label: 'No one shares the load', color: 'muted', text: 'Practical and emotional weight sits entirely on one person' },
        { label: 'Naming it restores trust', color: 'green', text: 'A diagnosis, or even one honest conversation, gives the experience a name and a reality' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'What helped me was deciding to become my own witness, on purpose. I started writing it down. Every flash, every sleepless night, every wave of low mood, with the date. Not to dwell, but to have a record outside my own doubting head. On paper, a pattern appeared. And a pattern is a fact. A pattern cannot be dismissed as me being dramatic.' },
      { text: 'I took that record to a gynaecologist. She read it, nodded, and said, this is a very clear picture of perimenopause. Those words did something enormous. Someone had looked at the evidence of my own body and confirmed it was real.' },
      { text: 'I also did something harder. I told two of my closest friends, plainly, that I was going through this and that I sometimes needed them to check on me, because there was no one at home to do it. They did not flinch. One of them said, of course, why did you not say so sooner. Now one of them messages me most mornings, just a small thing, are you sleeping. It is not a husband. It is better than nothing by an enormous distance.' },
      { text: 'You do not need a partner to go through this with dignity. But you do need a witness. If life has not given you one at home, you can build one. A notebook. A gynaecologist who listens. A friend who agrees to check in. I assembled mine out of the people and habits I already had, and it turned out to be enough.' },
    ]
  },

  anjali: {
    name: 'Anjali', age: 45, city: 'Delhi', occupation: 'Interior Designer',
    color: '#9C5D34',
    title: 'I Did Not Recognise the Woman in the Mirror',
    sections: [
      { text: 'I have always cared about how things look. It is my profession and it is my nature. So it unsettled me more than I want to admit when I began, slowly, to not recognise my own reflection.' },
      { text: 'It was not one dramatic morning. It was a hundred small ones. Clothes that had fit for years suddenly pulling in the wrong places. A softness around my middle that no amount of my usual walking would shift. My skin drier, my hair thinner, a face in the mirror that looked tired even when I was not.' },
      { text: 'I want to be honest about how much this hurt, because women are not supposed to admit it. We are supposed to be above vanity, to age gracefully, to not mind. I minded. I stood in front of my wardrobe some mornings and felt genuine grief, as though the body I had lived in comfortably my whole life had quietly been replaced with one I did not know how to dress.' },
      { ig: { head: "Why the Body Changes in Perimenopause", rows: [
        { label: 'Fat redistributes', color: 'peach', text: 'Falling oestrogen shifts where the body stores fat, often to the middle, even without eating more' },
        { label: 'Muscle is lost faster', color: 'peach', text: 'Hormonal changes make muscle harder to keep, which slows metabolism' },
        { label: 'Skin and hair change', color: 'muted', text: 'Less oestrogen means less collagen and moisture, so skin and hair feel different' },
        { label: 'Strength helps most', color: 'green', text: 'Building muscle, not punishing cardio, is what best supports the changing body' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'For a while I fought it the way I had always fought weight, with more walking and less food. It did not work, and worse, it made me feel like I was failing at something I had always been able to control. That was its own quiet blow.' },
      { text: 'What shifted things was learning why. A gynaecologist explained that in perimenopause, falling oestrogen actually changes where the body stores fat and how easily it holds muscle. It was not that I had suddenly become lazy or greedy. My body was following new instructions. That reframing alone loosened the grip of shame.' },
      { text: 'I stopped trying to starve my way back to my old shape and started, for the first time in my life, lifting weights. Not to be thin. To be strong. And something unexpected happened. As I got stronger, I stopped fighting my reflection quite so hard. I began to see a woman who was building something rather than losing something.' },
      { text: 'I am not going to pretend I have made complete peace with the mirror. Some mornings the grief still visits. But I dress the body I have now with the same care I once gave the old one, and I have learned that strength has its own kind of beauty, one that has nothing to do with the clothes fitting the way they used to.' },
    ]
  },

  ritu: {
    name: 'Ritu', age: 43, city: 'Kolkata', occupation: 'College Lecturer',
    color: '#46658A',
    title: 'We Drifted, and I Thought It Was Us',
    sections: [
      { text: 'My husband and I have a good marriage. Eighteen years, two children, the kind of quiet partnership that people take for granted until something shifts. And something shifted. For over a year, without either of us naming it, we drifted apart in the one area we had never had trouble.' },
      { text: 'It began with physical discomfort I was too embarrassed to explain. Intimacy started to hurt in a way it never had, a dryness, a rawness, that made me begin to avoid it. And because I could not find the words, I let him believe, through my turning away, that I had simply stopped wanting him.' },
      { text: 'He did not push. He is a kind man. But I watched him slowly conclude that this was who we were now, a couple who had cooled, and I saw it hurt him, and I let it happen because the truth felt too intimate and too much like a failing of my own body to say aloud.' },
      { ig: { head: "Why Intimacy Changes, and Why It Is Not Rejection", rows: [
        { label: 'Tissue thins and dries', color: 'peach', text: 'Falling oestrogen reduces natural lubrication and thins vaginal tissue, causing real pain' },
        { label: 'Desire can dip', color: 'peach', text: 'Hormonal changes, tiredness, and discomfort together lower libido, none of it about the partner' },
        { label: 'Avoidance reads as rejection', color: 'muted', text: 'Without words, a partner often misreads physical pain as emotional distance' },
        { label: 'Highly treatable', color: 'green', text: 'Moisturisers, lubricants, and local oestrogen restore comfort, and honesty restores closeness' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'The distance between us grew quietly for a year. I told myself it was normal, that all long marriages arrive here, that passion fades. But underneath I knew something more specific was wrong, and that I was letting a solvable problem calcify into a permanent one out of sheer embarrassment.' },
      { text: 'It was a blog, of all things, that gave me the words. I read a description of vaginal dryness in perimenopause and I sat very still, because someone had written down the exact thing I had been unable to say. It was physical. It was hormonal. It was common. It was treatable. And it was not, in any way, a verdict on my marriage.' },
      { text: 'I saw a gynaecologist, who was completely matter of fact about it and explained the treatments as if I had asked about a sore knee. Moisturisers, lubricants, a local oestrogen for the tissue itself. Within a few weeks the pain that had quietly rewritten my marriage was simply gone.' },
      { text: 'But the harder and more important repair was the conversation. I told my husband the truth, all of it, including that I had let him believe something untrue because I could not bear to explain. He was quiet for a while. Then he said, I thought you had stopped loving me. And I understood how much my silence had cost us both.' },
      { text: 'We found our way back, slowly, with more honesty than we had needed in years. If I could tell other women one thing it is this. The drifting may not be you and it may not be him. It may be your body, asking for help in the only language it has. Do not let embarrassment translate a treatable problem into a lost closeness.' },
    ]
  },

  shabnam: {
    name: 'Shabnam', age: 47, city: 'Ahmedabad', occupation: 'Boutique Owner',
    color: '#6B7A3D',
    title: 'A Friend Said the Word Before Any Doctor Did',
    sections: [
      { text: 'It was not a doctor who first told me what was happening to me. It was Farida, my friend of thirty years, across a table at our usual tea place, watching me fan myself with the menu for the third time.' },
      { text: 'She put down her cup and said, very simply, how old are you now, and how are your periods. I told her, a little surprised. She nodded slowly and said, I think you are in perimenopause. I went through it two years ago. Nobody tells you. So I am telling you.' },
      { text: 'I had been to two doctors by then. One had checked my thyroid and found nothing and sent me home. One had suggested I was stressed. Neither had said the word my oldest friend said to me over tea, without any medical degree, simply because she had lived it and paid attention.' },
      { ig: { head: "Why Shared Experience Reaches Women First", rows: [
        { label: 'Symptoms are dismissed', color: 'peach', text: 'Vague perimenopause symptoms are often missed or mislabelled as stress by busy clinics' },
        { label: 'Lived experience recognises it', color: 'peach', text: 'A woman who has been through it spots the pattern immediately in another' },
        { label: 'Permission to seek help', color: 'muted', text: 'Being believed by a peer gives women the confidence to push for proper care' },
        { label: 'Community changes outcomes', color: 'green', text: 'One honest conversation can shorten years of confusion into a clear next step' },
      ]}},
      { text: 'What Farida gave me that afternoon was not a diagnosis, exactly. She could not prescribe anything. What she gave me was recognition, and with it, permission. Permission to stop doubting myself. Permission to go back to a doctor and say, clearly, I think this is perimenopause, and I would like it taken seriously.' },
      { text: 'And that is what I did. Armed with the word, and with my friend\'s certainty behind me, I found a gynaecologist and said exactly that. It changed the entire tone of the appointment. She listened, she tested properly, and within a week I had the answer that two earlier visits had failed to give me.' },
      { text: 'But the deeper gift was realising how much we, as women, know that never gets passed on. Farida had gone through this two years before me, in silence, telling almost no one. If she had not chosen, that day, to break her own silence, I might have spent another year lost.' },
      { text: 'So we started talking. Really talking. In my boutique, between customers, with the women who come in around our age, I have started saying the word out loud, the way Farida said it to me. And again and again I watch a face change, the way mine must have changed, as someone realises there is a name for what they have been carrying alone.' },
      { text: 'Doctors matter. Tests matter. But sometimes the thing that saves you is an old friend who has been where you are, choosing not to stay quiet. I try to be that friend now, to as many women as I can. It costs nothing, and it gives back everything.' },
    ]
  },

};

